<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="62878" type="notes">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="62878">Notes</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="62878">
This Australian shrub is sometimes introduced in arid, harsh areas (e.g. Middle East, North Africa), mostly as an ornamental or as a windbreak, for erosion control, forage etc. It occasionally reproduces from seed, naturalises and is sometimes considered to be an undesirable weed. For example, it is a top ten prominent invader in the Nama-Karoo and Succulent Karoo biomes in South Africa (
<bibRefCitation author="Henderson, L" journalOrPublisher="Bothalia" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878" pagination="215 - 248" refId="B6509121" refString="Henderson, L, 2007. Invasive, naturalized and casual alien plants in southern Africa: a summary based on the Southern African Plant Invaders Atlas (SAPIA). Bothalia 37 (2): 215 - 248" title="Invasive, naturalized and casual alien plants in southern Africa: a summary based on the Southern African Plant Invaders Atlas (SAPIA)" volume="37" year="2007">Henderson 2007</bibRefCitation>
). In the Canary Islands, it was recently reported from Fuerteventura and Gran Canaria (
<bibRefCitation author="Verloove, F" journalOrPublisher="Collectanea Botanica" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878" pagination="59 - 82" refId="B6509955" refString="Verloove, F, 2013. New xenophytes from Gran Canaria (Canary Islands, Spain), with emphasis on naturalized and (potentially) invasive species. Collectanea Botanica 32: 59 - 82" title="New xenophytes from Gran Canaria (Canary Islands, Spain), with emphasis on naturalized and (potentially) invasive species" volume="32" year="2013">Verloove 2013</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Verloove, F" journalOrPublisher="Bouteloua" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878" pagination="38 - 42" refId="B6510051" refString="Verloove, F, Guiggi, A, 2013. Some new xenophytes from Fuerteventura (Canary Islands, Spain). Bouteloua 13: 38 - 42" title="Some new xenophytes from Fuerteventura (Canary Islands, Spain)" volume="13" year="2013">Verloove and Guiggi 2013</bibRefCitation>
). A small naturalised population with ca. 10 individuals has been known from Bajamar in Tenerife for many years.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="62878">
<taxonomicName class="Arachnida" family="Chenopodiaceae" genus="Atriplex" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Atriplex nummularia" order="Solifugae" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nummularia">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878">Atriplex nummularia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is much reminiscent of 
<taxonomicName genus="A." lsidName="A. halimus" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878" rank="species" species="halimus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878">A. halimus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
L., a species that naturally occurs in the Canary Islands. However, at least part of these populations undoubtedly refers to introduced races. For instance, a well-known expansive population from Las Chafiras (
<bibRefCitation author="Barone, R" journalOrPublisher="Botanica Macaronesica" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878" pagination="161 - 164" refId="B6456265" refString="Barone, R, 2003. Notas corologicas sobre dos especies de Atriplex L. (Chenopodiaceae) en Tenerife, Islas Canarias. Botanica Macaronesica 24: 161 - 164" title="Notas corologicas sobre dos especies de Atriplex L. (Chenopodiaceae) en Tenerife, Islas Canarias." volume="24" year="2003">Barone 2003</bibRefCitation>
), also in Tenerife, consists of diploids, whereas native populations are tetraploids (comm. A. Reyes-Betancort). The latter possibly correspond with var. 
<taxonomicName class="Arachnida" family="Chenopodiaceae" genus="Atriplex" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Atriplex halimus var. schweinfurthii" order="Solifugae" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="variety" species="halimus" variety="schweinfurthii">Atriplex halimus schweinfurthii</taxonomicName>
Boiss. (compare with 
<bibRefCitation author="Walker, D J" journalOrPublisher="Botanical Journal of the Linnean Society" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878" pagination="441 - 448" refId="B6510094" refString="Walker, D J, Monino, I, Gonzalez, E, Frayssinet, N, Correal, E, 2005. Determination of ploidy and nuclear DNA content in populations of Atriplex halimus (Chenopodiaceae). Botanical Journal of the Linnean Society 147 (4): 441 - 448" title="Determination of ploidy and nuclear DNA content in populations of Atriplex halimus (Chenopodiaceae)" volume="147" year="2005">Walker et al. 2005</bibRefCitation>
), a variety that occurs in arid zones with milder winters. 
<taxonomicName genus="A." lsidName="A. nummularia" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878" rank="species" species="nummularia">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878">A. nummularia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, in turn, is an octoploid (
<bibRefCitation author="Sampson, J F" journalOrPublisher="Biological Journal of the Linnean Society" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878" pagination="218 - 230" refId="B6509527" refString="Sampson, J F, Byrne, M, 2012. Genetic diversity and multiple origins of polyploid Atriplex nummularia Lindl. (Chenopodiaceae). Biological Journal of the Linnean Society 105 (1): 218 - 230" title="Genetic diversity and multiple origins of polyploid Atriplex nummularia Lindl. (Chenopodiaceae)" volume="105" year="2012">Sampson and Byrne 2012</bibRefCitation>
). It usually is dioecious and 
<taxonomicName genus="A." lsidName="A. halimus" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878" rank="species" species="halimus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878">A. halimus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
monoecious, although exceptions to this rule occur.
</paragraph>
